<chapter subject="Physics" id="110" name="Thermal Properties of Matter">
    <easy>
        <question>
            <text>Degrees of hotness or coldness of a body is called ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Temperature</option><option id="B">Heat</option><option id="C">Energy</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Measured using thermometers.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Form of energy that flows due to temperature difference is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Heat</option><option id="B">Work</option><option id="C">Power</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Energy in transit between systems.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>SI unit of Heat is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Joule (J)</option><option id="B">Calorie</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Consistent with energy units.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Standard fixed points of Celsius scale are ____.</text>
            <option id="A">0 C and 100 C</option><option id="B">273 K and 373 K</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Freezing and boiling points of water.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Device used to measure temperature is called ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Thermometer</option><option id="B">Calorimeter</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Based on thermometric properties.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>SI unit of Temperature is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Kelvin (K)</option><option id="B">Celsius</option><option id="C">Fahrenheit</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>The absolute scale.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Triple point of water is ____ K.</text>
            <option id="A">273.16</option><option id="B">273.15</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Unique state for three phase equilibrium.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Expansion of a body on heating is called ____ expansion.</text>
            <option id="A">Thermal</option><option id="B">Elastic</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Result of increased molecular kinetic energy.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Linear expansion occurs primarily in ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Solids (Rods/Wires)</option><option id="B">Liquids</option><option id="C">Gases</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>One-dimensional growth.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Coefficient of linear expansion is denoted by ____.</text>
            <option id="A">α (Alpha)</option><option id="B">β</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>ΔL = α L ΔT.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Coefficient of volume expansion is denoted by ____.</text>
            <option id="A">γ (Gamma)</option><option id="B">α</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>ΔV = γ V ΔT.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Relationship between linear and volume expansion for isotropic solid: γ = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">3 α</option><option id="B">2 α</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Derived from (1+αΔT)^3.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Water has minimum volume at ____ C.</text>
            <option id="A">4</option><option id="B">0</option><option id="C">100</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Due to anomalous expansion.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Water density is maximum at ____ C.</text>
            <option id="A">4</option><option id="B">0</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Inverse of volume trend.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Heat required to raise temp of 1kg substance by 1K is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Specific Heat Capacity</option><option id="B">Heat Capacity</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Material constant 's'.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Molar heat capacity is heat required for 1 ____ of substance per degree.</text>
            <option id="A">Mole</option><option id="B">Gram</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Units: J / (mol.K).</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Transition from solid to liquid is called ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Melting / Fusion</option><option id="B">Vaporization</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Occurs at melting point.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Transition from liquid to vapor is called ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Vaporization / Boiling</option><option id="B">Fusion</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Occurs at boiling point.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Heat involved in phase change without temp change is ____ heat.</text>
            <option id="A">Latent</option><option id="B">Specific</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>'Hidden' heat used for bond breaking.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Latent heat of fusion of ice is approx ____ J/kg.</text>
            <option id="A">3.33 x 10^5</option><option id="B">2.26 x 10^6</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Equivalent to 80 cal/g.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Latent heat of vaporization of water is approx ____ J/kg.</text>
            <option id="A">2.26 x 10^6</option><option id="B">3.33 x 10^5</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Equivalent to 540 cal/g.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Transfer of heat in solids by atomic vibrations is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Conduction</option><option id="B">Convection</option><option id="C">Radiation</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Requires direct contact.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Transfer of heat in fluids by bulk motion of matter is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Convection</option><option id="B">Conduction</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Natural or forced.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Transfer of heat through electromagnetic waves is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Radiation</option><option id="B">Conduction</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Can occur in vacuum.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Thermal conductivity SI unit is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">W / (m.K)</option><option id="B">J/K</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Watts per meter per Kelvin.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Perfect black body is a perfect ____ of all incident radiation.</text>
            <option id="A">Absorber</option><option id="B">Reflector</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Absorptivity = 1.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Stefan-Boltzmann Law: E = σ T ^ ____.</text>
            <option id="A">4</option><option id="B">2</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Energy emitted proportional to T^4.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Wien's Displacement Law: λ_max T = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Constant (b)</option><option id="B">Zero</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Peak wavelength decreases as T increases.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Rate of loss of heat proportional to temp difference is ____ Law.</text>
            <option id="A">Newton's Law of Cooling</option><option id="B">Stefan's Law</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Valid for small temp differences.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Conversion from Celsius to Kelvin: K = C + ____.</text>
            <option id="A">273.15</option><option id="B">32</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Absolute zero offset.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Temperature at which water, ice and steam coexist is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Triple point</option><option id="B">Normal boiling point</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Used to define Kelvin scale.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Expansion coefficient relative sizes: α ____ β ____ γ.</text>
            <option id="A">&lt; , &lt;</option><option id="B">&gt; , &gt;</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>1 : 2 : 3 ratio.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Pyrometer is used to measure very ____ temperatures.</text>
            <option id="A">High (e.g. Furnaces)</option><option id="B">Low</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Uses radiation property.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Boiling point of liquid ____ with increase in pressure.</text>
            <option id="A">Increases</option><option id="B">Decreases</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
